es give out prizes more often, due to a mechanical malfunction; and that the prizes are enormous! However, there is no evidence that such a machine exists, and if it does, the tiniest sign of malfunction would lead the owners to remove it from the casino floor.\r\n\r\nAnd with computerized slots, this is even more unlikely! The state-of-the-art software built in the modern games would notice any kind of corruption, and alert the providers to either fix it or make the slot unavailable.\r\n<h3>Winning Time</h3>\r\nAnother common myth is that casinos tighten slots on weekends and holidays, to make sure not too many jackpots get hit. However, the time and bureaucracy required to change a specific slot feature are substantial. Legal casinos would not do this. Also, by checking the paytable, you can get some important info, and see for yourself if they’re any different from the last time you played!\r\n\r\nSo instead of focusing on beating the computer, maybe we should concentrate on the kinds of things that really can help us improve our chances.\r\n<h2>Strategies</h2>\r\nThe wisest strategy for any game is to come prepared and informed. The best tactics are to fight the battles that you can, and make the most out of your situation. So let’s apply this approach to the slots and devise a couple of tips that can come in handy.\r\n<h3>Scouting</h3>\r\nBefore you play for actual money, try many of the free play options that casinos offer. We already said that slots are run by computers now, and every machine is different than the other. To understand how jackpot work, but also multipliers, wilds, scatters, and bonuses, find a slot you like and explore the demo mode. This will make it familiar, and you won’t come across any unpleasant surprises when you start betting.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-301\" src=\"http://aussieplay-blog.local/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/3783.jpg\" alt=\"Guy playing slots\" width=\"480\" height=\"269\" />\r\n<h3>Thrifting</h3>\r\nIn this highly competitive gaming industry, casinos are everything but stingy when it comes to promotions. It might be good to become a member of a casino club or subscribe to their newsletters. This is where they advertise and give away a bunch of free stuff, like free games and credits. Use this as much as possible, because you can even win something without investing! Or else, even if you don’t win, you still get a free lesson in gaming.\r\n<h3>RTP First</h3>\r\nReturn to Player is something you need to check every time you face a slot. It is a percentage of the total bet that is returned to players over time. Just to clarify this: casinos never pay out the full amount wagered.\r\n\r\nFor example, 100 dollars have been wagered, and the RTP is 97%. The players will get 97 dollars. Sound unfair? Well, in theory, you can bet one dollar and get a multi-million jackpot on your first spin; and then never return to that casino! So, the percentage is there to ensure that each casino can avoid heavy losses in the long run.\r\n\r\nMaybe it’s easier to understand this if we put it in a table.\r\n\r\n[supsystic-tables id=4]\r\n\r\nSo two almost identical machines can give totally different amounts, purely because the manufacturers can produce slots that are pretty similar, yet nonetheless have dissimilar features. Still: the RTP is available for every slot anyway, so there are no excuses. Anything above 96% is good!\r\n<h3>Choose Your Volatility</h3>\r\nSome slots pay out more often but with smaller prizes, and we call them low-volatility machines. Others give big rewards, but not as frequently. These ones are known as high-volatility slots.\r\n\r\nThe critical thing here is to decide which tempo you prefer. If you’re more motivated to chase frequent but lower wins that choose a low-volatility slot. If you have the patience and funds to chase that grand prize, then go for the highly volatile option.\r\n\r\nTo be sure which one it is, consult the paytable. If there’s a big disparity between the highest and lowest paying symbols, it’s a high-volatility machine.\r\n<h3>Bankroll Rules</h3>\r\nWhen you start playing with real money, things may get hectic! So it’s crucial to implement a bankroll strategy to help you keep things in order. It’s pretty clear by now that there are not many things we can control when it comes to slot games. But fortunately, money management is the one thing we really can exercise control over!\r\n\r\nOf all the tips we emphasise for the gambling community to follow, the most useful one is to make a solid bankroll plan. So here are some simple guidelines:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Set a budget and do not deviate from it. Getting into money trouble is the last thing you need! Controlling your assets can help you stay in the game longer, and helps give you a more realistic chance of winning.</li>\r\n 	<li>“Less is more” is not always a good rule when it comes to slots. If you’re in it to get the jackpot, you may have to invest pretty hard in hitting it big. Some jackpots require the maximum bet to be won, so you may need to come up with a solid strategy on how to spend your money. You don’t want to squander your cash; but if you’re too stingy, you may as well be playing for peanuts!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>To Slot It Up</h2>\r\nSlots are super fun, and you should try them if you are interested in gaming. You just need to be sure you understand the game and what to expect of it. So it is vital to set your limits. This goes for the money and the time you invest in gambling.\r\n\r\nSlots are potentially addictive and you need to pay attention, in order not to overdo it. Any kind of problem you develop will ultimately spoil your fun and take away the thrill of playing. That is why we should be wise and keep aware that, although we can earn a lot, we can also lose a lot! Because it’s still just a game. So if we stop enjoying it, we should probably stop playing it; at least for a while!', 'How to Play Slots', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '292-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-12-06 20:01:59', '2019-12-06 18:01:59', '', 292, 'http://aussieplay-blog.local/bez-kategorii/292-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
