e casino is regulated and licensed by some regulatory body. Furthermore, all the games are tested, and this is always done by third parties, to ensure objectivity. Most aspects of online casinos are checked regularly; and this includes RNGs, of course, since they power most of the games.\r\n\r\nIn fact, there are many businesses that work in the field of testing online gambling games. They work tirelessly to make sure that the various casinos they test are suitable places to gamble your hard-earned money.\r\n\r\nOne of those businesses is Technical Systems Testing (TST). They specialise in various aspects of testing, like live dealer testing, RNG test, etc. What’s more, TST are reputed to have the best RNG evaluations on the market.\r\n\r\nIt’s easy to see which casinos want to provide a safe and fair space for us to have fun and which ones just want to take your hard-earned money. If they’re unlicensed or uncertified, or at the very least don’t have a badge, they should be approached with caution.\r\n<h3>Betting Strategies &amp; The Lack of Physics in Online Roulette</h3>\r\nThere are many betting strategies in roulette. One such example is the infamous Martingale system, which is based on the principle of doubling down after a loss. This is a basic strategy, which is scorned by professional gamblers. Indeed, plenty of casinos advertise the fact that they allow the Martingale, which really should speak volumes about its efficiency!\r\n\r\nWhen dealing with RNGs, most betting strategies make the same mistake — they assume each number on the wheel is equally probable. Yet, casinos have a house edge of 2.7% in European roulette and a whopping 5.26% in American roulette (due to the double zero); naturally, this means the various betting strategies gamblers use inevitably fail over time.\r\n\r\nAnd since online roulette isn’t happening in the real world, physics is simply out of the question. There is no way for you to predict how the ball will land. Since there is no ball and there is nowhere for it to land, it’s just an RNG selecting a number. The animations are just for aesthetic purposes.\r\n<h2>Summary</h2>\r\nThere you go then! Hope you know what RNGs are now. Now that I’ve shed some light on the subject, you can go and gamble away without any unfounded suspicions.\r\n\r\nSo go out now and enjoy yourself — have a bit of fun! Good luck, and play smart!', 'Random Number Generators (RNG) — The Cornerstones of Online Fairness', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2019-12-19 11:31:59', '2019-12-19 09:31:59', '', 0, 'http://aussieplay-blog.local/?p=578', 0, 'post', '', 0);
